    "statement": "In the first decades of the twentieth century, members of the so-called \"Munich and G&ouml;ttingen circles\" of phenomenology made important contributions to various areas of philosophical research, including philosophy of mind, philosophy of language, philosophy of action, epistemology, social philosophy, axiology, and ontology. Some of the most prominent members of these circles are Alfred Brunswig, Theodor Conrad, Hedwig Conrad-Martius, Johannes Daubert, August Gallinger, Moritz Geiger, Roman Ingarden, Alexander Pf&auml;nder, Adolf Reinach, Wilhelm Schapp, Max Scheler, Kurt Stavenhagen, Edith Stein, Dietrich von Hildebrand, and Gerda Walther. The ideas of these authors were influenced by thinkers such as Henri Bergson, Bernard Bolzano, Franz Brentano, Theodor Lipps, Hermann Lotze, Anton Marty, Alexius Meinong--and, perhaps more significantly, by the work of Edmund Husserl. Some of the most original insights provided by what has also been characterized as \"early\" or \"realist phenomenology\" concern the notion of intentionality, which is the property of some mental states whereby they are directed towards objects and states of affairs. Many early phenomenologists claimed that there are radically different kinds of intentionality (and, by extension, of intentional acts), which do not fall under a unitary genus. This idea is applied to advance the understanding not only of infra-subjective intentionality--through investigations of perceptual experiences, linguistic acts of thinking, various kinds of reason-responsive attitudes, and their interrelations--but also of inter-subjective intentionality, through the development of insightful theories of social and speech acts, empathy, and collective intentionality. Early phenomenologists understood the investigation of mental experiences as part of a general theory of objects or ontology. Their contributions to ontology are characterised by a commitment to metaphysical realism: there are objects and facts, which exist independently of anyone's beliefs, mental states or conceptual schemes, and they instantiate essential properties. The two main categories of phenomenological ontology, to which several members of both circles devoted extensive research, are that of objects and states of affairs.",
